# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: editorconfig
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Reducing the cost of software maintenance is the most often cited reason for following coding conventions.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Software peer review frequently involves reading source code.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] This type of peer review is primarily a defect detection activity.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] By definition, only the original author of a piece of code has read the source file before the code is submitted for review.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Code that is written using consistent guidelines is easier for other reviewers to understand and assimilate, improving the efficacy of the defect detection process.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Even for the original author, consistently coded software eases maintainability.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] There is no guarantee that an individual will remember the precise rationale for why a particular piece of code was written in a certain way long after the code was originally written.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Consistent use of whitespace improves readability and reduces the time it takes to understand the software.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Where coding conventions have been specifically designed to produce high-quality code, and have then been formally adopted, they then become coding standards.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Specific styles, irrespective of whether they are commonly adopted, do not automatically produce good quality code.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Complexity is a factor going against security.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] The management of complexity includes the following basic principle: minimize the amount of code written during the project development.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] This prevents unnecessary work which prevents unnecessary cost, both upfront and downstream.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] This is simply because if there is less code, it is less work not only to create the application, but also to maintain it.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Complexity is managed both at the design stage (how the project is architectured) and at the development stage (by having simpler code).
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] If the coding is kept basic and simple then the complexity will be minimised.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Very often this is keeping the coding as 'physical' as possible - coding in a manner that is very direct and not highly abstract.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] This produces optimal code that is easy to read and follow.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Complexity can also be avoided simply by not using complicated tools for simple jobs.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] The more complex the code is the more likely it is to be buggy, the more difficult the bugs are to find and the more likely there are to be hidden bugs.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Refactoring refers to a software maintenance activity where source code is modified to improve readability or improve its structure.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Software is often refactored to bring it into conformance with a team's stated coding standards after its initial release.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Any change that does not alter the behavior of the software can be considered refactoring.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Common refactoring activities are changing variable names, renaming methods, moving methods or whole classes and breaking large methods (or functions) into smaller ones.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Agile software development methodologies plan for regular (or even continuous) refactoring making it an integral part of the team software development process.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Coding conventions allow programmers to have simple scripts or programs whose job is to process source code for some purpose other than compiling it into an executable.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] It is common practice to count the software size (Source lines of code) to track current project progress or establish a baseline for future project estimates.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Consistent coding standards can, in turn, make the measurements more consistent.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Special tags within source code comments are often used to process documentation, two notable examples are javadoc and doxygen.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] The tools specify the use of a set of tags, but their use within a project is determined by convention.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Coding conventions simplify writing new software whose job is to process existing software.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Use of static code analysis has grown consistently since the 1950s.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Some of the growth of this class of development tools stems from increased maturity and sophistication of the practitioners themselves (and the modern focus on safety and security), but also from the nature of the languages themselves.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] All software practitioners must grapple with the problem of organizing and managing a large number of sometimes complex instructions.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] For all but the smallest software projects, source code (instructions) are partitioned into separate files and frequently among many directories.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] It was natural for programmers to collect closely related functions (behaviors) in the same file and to collect related files into directories.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] As software development shifted from purely procedural programming (such as found in FORTRAN) towards more object-oriented constructs (such as found in C++), it became the practice to write the code for a single (public) class in a single file (the 'one class per file' convention).
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Java has gone one step further - the Java compiler returns an error if it finds more than one public class per file.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] A convention in one language may be a requirement in another.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Language conventions also affect individual source files.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Each compiler (or interpreter) used to process source code is unique.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] The rules a compiler applies to the source creates implicit standards.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] For example, Python code is much more consistently indented than, say Perl, because whitespace (indentation) is actually significant to the interpreter.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Python does not use the brace syntax Perl uses to delimit functions.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Changes in indentation serve as the delimiters.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] The reason is that in Tcl, curly braces are not used only to delimit functions as in C or Java.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] More generally, curly braces are used to group words together into a single argument.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] In Tcl, the *word* **while** takes two arguments, a *condition* and an *action*.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] In the example above, **while** is missing its second argument, its *action* (because the Tcl also uses the newline character to delimit the end of a command).
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] There are a large number of coding conventions; see *Coding Style* for numerous examples and discussion.
[src:editorconfig/coding-conventions] Coding standards include the CERT C Coding Standard, MISRA C, High Integrity C++.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] A **configuration file**, also known as **config file**, is a file that stores data used to configure a software system such as an application, a server or an operating system.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Some applications provide a tool to create, modify, and verify the syntax of their configuration files – sometimes via graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] For context, system administrators may be expected to create and modify text config files via a text editor.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] For server processes and operating-system settings, there is often no standard tool, but operating systems may provide graphical interfaces such as YaST or debconf.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Some computer programs only read their configuration files at startup.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Others periodically check the configuration files for changes.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Users can instruct some programs to re-read the configuration files and apply the changes to the current process, or indeed to read arbitrary files as a configuration file.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] There are no definitive standards or strong conventions.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] In general, a config file can have any format.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] The format that applies to a particular system is determined by the design of that system.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Often, a standardized format is used since it allows for using tools designed for the format even if not designed for the consuming system.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] In particular, general-purpose serialization formats, such as JSON, XML, and YAML, are often used in open-source and platform-neutral software.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] The specifications for these formats are generally publicly available to support wide-spread use.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] The following table compares notable formats used for configuration data.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] The *syntax typing* column indicates whether the syntax supports data types.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] A format has syntax-typing if a value's type is specified by syntax – e.g.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] `true` is a Boolean while `"true"` is a string.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] A format does not have syntax-typing if a value's type is based on semantics – e.g.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] `true` and `"true"` are both Boolean if the parser expects a Boolean.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Opinions on the value of syntax-typing vary.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] The following are examples of config files organized by the operating systems on which they are commonly used.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Many different file formats are used on Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Even so, there is a strong tradition of using human-editable, plain text formats including simple key–value pair.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Filename extensions of `.cnf`, `.conf`, `.cfg`, `.cf` or `.ini` are often used.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Many formats allow comments, in which case, individual settings can be disabled by prepending with the comment character.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Often the default configuration files contain extensive internal documentation in the form of comments and man files are also typically used to document the format and options available.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] System-wide software often uses configuration files stored in `/etc`, while user applications often use a "dotfile" – a file or directory in the home directory prefixed with a period, which in Unix hides the file or directory from casual listing.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Since this causes pollution, newer user applications generally make their own folder in the `.config` directory, a standardized subdirectory of the home directory.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Similar to config files, a run command (rc) shell script can configure a shell session.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Often, such scripts are named with an `rc` suffix after the consuming program's name such as `.xinitrc`, `.vimrc`, `.bashrc`, `xsane.rc`.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] By contrast, IBM's AIX uses an Object Data Manager (ODM) database to store much of its system settings.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] MS-DOS primarily relied on the `CONFIG.SYS` config file, a plain text file with simple key–value pairs (e.g.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] MS-DOS 6 introduced the INI-file format.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Similar to an rc file, the batch file named `AUTOEXEC.BAT` ran commands on startup.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Both these files were retained up to Windows 98SE, which still ran on top of MS-DOS.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] DOS applications used a wide variety of individual configuration files, most of them binary, proprietary and undocumented - and there were no common conventions or formats.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Early Windows operating systems heavily utilized plain-text INI files which served as the primary mechanism to configure the operating system and applications.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] The APIs to read and write from these still exist in Windows, but after 1993, Microsoft began to steer developers away from using INI files and toward storing settings in the registry, a hierarchical database to store configuration settings, which was introduced with Windows NT.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Later systems use XML and other formats instead of the registry.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] The Property List is the standard configuration file format in macOS (as well as in iOS, NeXTSTEP, GNUstep and Cocoa applications).
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] It uses the filename extension `.plist`.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] IBM's OS/2 uses a binary format, also with a .INI suffix, but this differs from the Windows versions.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] It contains a list of lists of untyped key–value pairs.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Two files control system-wide settings: OS2.INI and OS2SYS.INI.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] Application developers can choose whether to use them or to create a specific file for their applications.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] HarmonyOS and OpenHarmony-based operating systems use JSON config files, named `config.json`.
[src:editorconfig/configuration-file] The platform IDE, DevEco Studio, provides methods for editing `config.json`.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] EditorConfig helps maintain consistent coding styles for multiple developers working on the same project across various editors and IDEs.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] The EditorConfig project consists of **a file format** for defining coding styles and a collection of **text editor plugins** that enable editors to read the file format and adhere to defined styles.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] EditorConfig files are easily readable and they work nicely with version control systems.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Below is an example `.editorconfig` file setting end-of-line and indentation styles for Python and JavaScript files.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Check the Wiki for some real-world examples of projects using EditorConfig files.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] When opening a file, EditorConfig plugins look for a file named `.editorconfig` (all lowercase) in the directory of the opened file and in every parent directory.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] A search for `.editorconfig` files will stop if the root filepath is reached or an EditorConfig file with `root=true` is found.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] EditorConfig files are read top to bottom and the most recent rules found take precedence.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Properties from matching EditorConfig sections are applied in the order they were read, so properties in closer files take precedence.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] EditorConfig files use an INI format that is compatible with the format used by Python configparser Library, but `[` and `]` are allowed in the section names.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] The section names are filepath globs (case sensitive), similar to the format accepted by gitignore.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Only forward slashes (`/`, not backslashes) are used as path separators and octothorpes (`#`) or semicolons (`;`) are used for comments.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] EditorConfig files should be UTF-8 encoded, with either `CRLF` or `LF` line separators.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Filepath glob patterns and currently-supported EditorConfig properties are explained below.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Special characters can be escaped with a backslash so they won't be interpreted as wildcard patterns.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Note that not all properties are supported by every plugin.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] The wiki has a complete list of properties.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Currently all properties and values are case-insensitive.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Generally, if a property is not specified, the editor settings will be used, i.e.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] EditorConfig takes no effect on that part.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] For any property, a value of `unset` is to remove the effect of that property, even if it has been set before.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] For example, add `indent_size = unset` to undefine **`indent_size`** property (and use editor default).
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] It is acceptable and often preferred to leave certain EditorConfig properties unspecified.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] For example, **`tab_width`** need not be specified unless it differs from the value of **`indent_size`**.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Also, when **`indent_style`** is set to `tab`, it may be desirable to leave **`indent_size`** unspecified so readers may view the file using their preferred indentation width.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Additionally, if a property is not standardized in your project (**`end_of_line`** for example), it may be best to leave it blank.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] These editors come bundled with native support for EditorConfig.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] To use EditorConfig with one of these editors, you will need to install a plugin.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] To use EditorConfig with one of these headless tools, you will need to install a plugin.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] EditorConfig editor plugins must follow the specifications.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] They can be developed with the help from one of the EditorConfig core libraries.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] The EditorConfig core libraries accept as input the file being edited, find and parse relevant `.editorconfig` files, and pass back the properties that should be used.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Please ignore any unrecognized properties and property values in your editor plugin for future compatibility, since new properties and permitted values will be added in the future.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] If you are planning on creating a new plugin, use the mailing list to let us know so we can help out and link to your plugin once it's created.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] If you plan on using one of the EditorConfig cores as a library or command line interface, the C library documentation, Python library documentation or Java library documentation may be helpful.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] More details can be found on the Plugin-How-To wiki page.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] We have many awesome contributors contributing to the specification, core library, and plugins.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] For an up-to-date list, please see the Board Members page and the contributor pages of the specification, core libraries, and plugins.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Most of of EditorConfig logos were drawn by Kat On and Amon Keishima.
[src:editorconfig/editorconfig-org] Website were mainly by Trey Hunner and Hong Xu.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In computer programming, **indentation style** is a convention or style, governing the indentation of lines of source code.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] An indentation style generally specifies a consistent number of whitespace characters before each line of a block, so that the lines of code appear to be related, and dictates whether to use spaces or tabs as the indentation character.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This article primarily addresses styles for free-form programming languages.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] As the name implies, such language code need not follow an indentation style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Indentation is a secondary notation that is often intended to lower cognitive load for a programmer to understand the structure of the code.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Indentation can clarify the separation between the code executed based on control flow.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Structured languages, such as Python and occam, use indentation to determine the structure instead of using braces or keywords; this is termed the off-side rule.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In such languages, indentation is meaningful to the language processor (such as compiler or interpreter).
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] A programmer must conform to the language's indentation rules although may be free to choose indentation size.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This article focuses on curly-bracket languages (that delimit blocks with curly brackets, a.k.a. curly braces, a.k.a. braces) and in particular C-family languages, but a convention used for one language can be adapted to another language.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] For example, a language that uses `BEGIN` and `END` keywords instead of braces can be adapted by treating `BEGIN` the same as the open brace and so on.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Indentation style only applies to text-based languages.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Visual programming languages generally do not use indentation in the same way.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Despite the ubiquitous use of indentation styles, little research has been conducted on its value.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] First experiments, conducted by Weissman in 1974, did not show any effect.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In 2023, an experiment by Morzeck et al. showed a significant positive effect for nested `if` statements where non-indented code required on average 179% more time to read than indented code.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] A follow up-experiment by Hanenberg et al. confirmed a large effect (although in that experiment non-indented code just took 113% more time to read) and revealed that the differences in reading times can be explained by the code that can be skipped (for indented code).
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In another experiment on JSON objects non-indented code took even 544% more time to read.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The table below illustrates how different brace placement styles interact with indentation in control structures.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] For consistency, indentation size for example code is 4 spaces even though this varies by coding convention.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The Kernighan & Ritchie (K&R) style is commonly used for C and C++ code and is the basis for many derivative styles.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] It is used in the original Unix kernel, Kernighan and Ritchie's book *The C Programming Language*, as well as Kernighan and Plauger's book *The Elements of Programming Style*.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Although *The C Programming Language* does not explicitly define this style, it follows it consistently.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In this style, a function has its opening and closing braces on their own lines and with the same indentation as the declaration, while the statements in the body of the function are indented an additional level.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] A multi-statement block inside a function, however, has its opening brace on the same line as its control clause while the closing brace remains on its own line unless followed by a keyword such as `else` or `while`.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The non-aligned braces of the multi-line blocks are nicknamed "Egyptian braces" (or "Egyptian brackets") for their resemblance to arms in some fanciful poses of ancient Egyptians.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] A single-statement block does not have braces, which is a cause of easy-to-miss bugs such as the goto fail bug.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The *One True Brace Style* (abbreviated 1TBS or OTBS) is a variant of K&R style where braces are *not* omitted for a single-statement block.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Although not required by languages such as C/C++, using braces for single-statement blocks ensures inserting a new statement does not result in control flow that disagrees with indenting, as seen for example in Apple's infamous goto fail bug.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The Linux kernel source tree is styled in a variant of K&R.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Linus Torvalds advises contributors to follow it.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] A significant body of Java code uses a variant of the K&R style in which the opening brace is on the same line not only for the blocks inside a function, but also for class or method declarations.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style is widespread largely because Sun Microsystems's original style guides used this K&R variant, and as a result, most of the standard source code for the Java API is written in this style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] It is also a popular indentation style for ActionScript and JavaScript, along with the Allman style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Bjarne Stroustrup adapted the K&R style for C++ in his books, such as *Programming: Principles and Practice using C++* and *The C++ Programming Language*.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Unlike the variants above, Stroustrup does not use a "cuddled else".
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Stroustrup does not indent the labels `public:` and `private:`.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Also, in this style, while the opening brace of a function starts on a new line, the opening brace of a class is on the same line as the class name.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Stroustrup allows writing short functions all on one line.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Stroustrup style is a named indentation style available in the editor Emacs.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Stroustrup encourages a K&R-derived style layout with C++ as stated in his modern *C++ Core Guidelines*.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) operating systems uses a style that is sometimes termed "kernel normal form" (KNF).
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Although mostly intended for kernel code, it is also widely used in userland code.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] It is essentially a thoroughly documented variant of K&R style as used in the Bell Labs version 6 & 7 Unix source code.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The SunOS kernel and userland uses a similar indentation style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Like KNF, this also was based on AT&T style documents and is sometimes termed Bill Joy Normal Form.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The SunOS guideline was published in 1996; ANSI C is discussed briefly.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The correctness of the indentation of a list of source files can be verified by the *cstyle* program written by Bill Shannon.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In this style, the hard tabulator (ts in vi) is kept at eight columns, while a soft tabulator is often defined as a helper also (sw in vi), and set at four.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The hard tabulators are used to indent code blocks, while a soft tabulator (four spaces) of additional indentation is used for all continuing lines that must be split over multiple lines.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Moreover, function calls do not use a space before the parenthesis, although C-language native statements such as `if`, `while`, `do`, `switch` and `return` do (in the case where `return` is used with parens).
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Functions that declare no local variables in their top-level block should also leave an empty line after their opening block brace.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The Allman style is named after Eric Allman.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] It is also sometimes termed *BSD style* since Allman wrote many of the utilities for BSD Unix (although this should not be confused with the different "BSD KNF style"; see above).
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style puts the brace associated with a control statement on the next line, indented to the same level as the control statement.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Statements within the braces are indented to the next level.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style is similar to the standard indentation used by the Pascal languages and Transact-SQL, where the braces are equivalent to the keywords `begin` and `end`.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Consequences of this style are that the indented code is clearly set apart from the containing statement by lines that are almost all whitespace and the closing brace lines up in the same column as the opening brace.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Some people feel this makes it easy to find matching braces.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The blocking style also delineates the block of code from the associated control statement.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Commenting out or removing a control statement or block of code, or code refactoring, are all less likely to introduce syntax errors via dangling or missing braces.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Also, it is consistent with brace placement for the outer-function block.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Allman-8 uses the 8-space indentation tabs and 80-column limit of the Linux Kernel variant of K&R.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The style purportedly helps improve readability on projectors.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Also, the indentation size and column restriction help create a visual cue for identifying excessive nesting of code blocks.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] These advantages combine to help provide newer developers and learners implicit guidance to manage code complexity.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The Whitesmiths style, also sometimes termed Wishart style, was originally used in the documentation for the first commercial C compiler, the Whitesmiths Compiler.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] It was also popular in the early days of Windows, since it was used in three influential Windows programming books, *Programmer's Guide to Windows* by Durant, Carlson & Yao, *Programming Windows* by Petzold, and *Windows 3.0 Power Programming Techniques* by Norton & Yao.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Whitesmiths, along with Allman, were claimed to have been the most common bracing styles in 1991 by the Jargon File, with roughly equal popularity at the time.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style puts the brace associated with a control statement on the next line, indented.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Statements within the braces are indented to the same level as the braces.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Like Ratliff style, the closing brace is indented the same as statements within the braces.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The advantages of this style are similar to those of the Allman style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Blocks are clearly set apart from control statements.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The alignment of the braces with the block emphasizes that the full block is conceptually, and programmatically, one compound statement.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Indenting the braces emphasizes that they are subordinate to the control statement.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The ending brace no longer lines up with the statement, but instead with the opening brace.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] `else if` are treated as statement, much like the `#elif` preprocessor statement.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Like the Allman and Whitesmiths styles, GNU style puts braces on a line by themselves, indented by two spaces, except when opening a function definition, where they are not indented.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In either case, the contained code is indented by two spaces from the braces.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Popularised by Richard Stallman, the layout may be influenced by his background of writing Lisp code.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In Lisp, the equivalent to a block (a progn) is a first-class data entity, and giving it its own indentation level helps to emphasize that, whereas in C, a block is only syntax.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style can also be found in some ALGOL and XPL programming language textbooks from the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Although not indentation per se, GNU coding style also includes a space after a function name – before the left parenthesis of an argument list.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style combines the advantages of Allman and Whitesmiths, thereby removing the possible Whitesmiths disadvantage of braces not standing out from the block.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] One disadvantage is that the ending brace no longer lines up with the statement it conceptually belongs to.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Another possible disadvantage is that it might waste space by using two visual levels of indents for one conceptual level, but in reality this is unlikely because, in systems with single-level indentation, each level is usually at least 4 spaces, same as 2 * 2 spaces in GNU style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The GNU Coding Standards recommend this style, and nearly all maintainers of GNU project software use it.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The GNU Emacs text editor and the GNU systems' indent command will reformat code according to this style by default.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Those who do not use GNU Emacs, or similarly extensible/customisable editors, may find that the automatic indentation settings of their editor are unhelpful for this style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] However, many editors defaulting to KNF style cope well with the GNU style when the tab width is set to two spaces; likewise, GNU Emacs adapts well to KNF style by simply setting the tab width to eight spaces.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In both cases, automatic reformatting destroys the original spacing, but automatic line indenting will work properly.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Steve McConnell, in his book Code Complete, advises against using this style: he marks a code sample which uses it with a "Coding Horror" icon, symbolizing especially dangerous code, and states that it impedes readability.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The Linux kernel coding style documentation also recommends against this style, urging readers to burn a copy of the GNU coding standards as a "great symbolic gesture".
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The 1997 edition of *Computing Concepts with C++ Essentials* by Cay S.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Horstmann adapts Allman by placing the first statement of a block on the same line as the opening brace.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style is also used in examples in Jensen and Wirth's *Pascal User Manual and Report*.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style combines the advantages of Allman by keeping the vertical alignment of the braces for readability, and identifying blocks easily, with the saving of a line of the K&R style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] However, the 2003 edition now uses Allman style throughout.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This is the style used most commonly in the language Pico by its designers.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Pico lacks return statements, and uses semicolons as statement separators instead of terminators.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of saving screen real estate with K&R style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] An added advantage is that the starting and closing braces are consistent in application (both share space with a line of code), relative to K&R style, where one brace shares space with a line of code and one brace has a line alone.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Wayne Ratliff, the original programmer behind the popular dBase-II and -III fourth-generation programming languages, discussed a style that is like 1TBS but the closing brace lines up with the indentation of the nested block.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] He indicated that the style was originally documented in material from Digital Research Inc.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style has sometimes been termed *banner* style, possibly for the resemblance to a banner hanging from a pole.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Kernighan and Plauger use this style in the Ratfor code in *Software Tools*.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The following styles may be considered to be "derived" C styles, in the sense that they derive significant influence from the indentation styles of other, non-C languages.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] They might be applied to C code written as part of a project *mostly* written in one of these other languages, where maintaining a consistent *look and feel* to the project's core code overrides considerations of using more conventional C style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] While GNU style is sometimes characterized as C code indented by a Lisp programmer, one might even go so far as to insert closing braces together in the last line of a block.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style makes indentation the only way to distinguish blocks of code, but has the advantage of containing no uninformative lines.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This could easily be called the Lisp style because this style is very common in Lisp code.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In Lisp, the grouping of identical braces at the end of expression trees is meant to signify that it is not the user's job to visually track nesting levels, only to understand the structure of the tree.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This is also because, braces aside, Lisp is conventionally a very terse language, omitting even common forms of simple boilerplate code as uninformative, such as the `else` keyword in an `if : then | else` block, instead rendering it uniformly as `(if expr1 expr2 expr3)`.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Note: `progn` is a procedure for evaluating multiple sub-expressions sequentially for effects, while discarding all but the final (nth) return value.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] If all return values are desired, the `values` procedure would be used.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Haskell layout can make the placement of braces optional, although braces and semicolons are allowed in the language.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Usually the braces and semicolons are omitted for procedural `do` sections and the program text in general, but the style is commonly used for lists, records and other syntactic elements made up of some pair of parentheses or braces, which are separated with commas or semicolons.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] If code following the keywords `where`, `let`, or `of` omits braces and semicolons, then indentation is significant.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] APL style C resembles the terse style of APL code, and is commonly used in their implementations.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This style was pioneered by Arthur Whitney, and is heavily used in the implementation of K, Arthur's own project.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] The J programming language is implemented in this style as well.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Notably, not all implementations of APL use this style of C, namely: GNU APL and Dyalog APL.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In addition to APL style C indentation, typically the names are shortened to either single or double characters: To reduce the amount of indentation, and expressions spanning multiple lines.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Typically, programmers use the same width of whitespace to indent each block of code with commonly used widths varying from 1 to 4 spaces.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] An experiment performed on PASCAL code in 1983, found that indentation size significantly affected comprehensibility.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Indentation sizes between 2 and 4 characters proved optimal.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Although they both affect the general layout of code, indentation *size* is independent of the indentation *style* discussed here.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Typically, a programmer uses a text editor that provides tab stops at fixed intervals (a number of spaces), to assist in maintaining whitespace according to a style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Sometimes the programmer stores the code with tab characters – one for each tab key press or they store a sequence of spaces equal in number to the tab width.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Storing tab characters in code can cause visual misalignment when viewed in different contexts, which counters the value of the indentation style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Programmers lack consensus on storing tab characters.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Proponents of storing tab characters cite ease of typing and smaller text files since a single tab character serves the purpose of multiple spaces.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Opponents, such as Jamie Zawinski, state that using spaces instead increases cross-platform portability.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Others, such as the writers of the WordPress coding standards, state the opposite: that hard tabs increase portability.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] A survey of the top 400,000 repositories on GitHub found that spaces are more common.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Many text editors, including Notepad++, TextEdit, Emacs, vi, and nano, can be configured to either store tab characters when entered via the tab key or to convert them to spaces (based on the configured tab width) so that tab characters are not added to the file when the tab key is pressed.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Some editors can convert tab to space characters and vice versa.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Some text file pagers, such as less, can be configured for a tab width.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Some tools such as expand/unexpand can convert on the fly via filters.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] A tool can automate formatting code per an indentation style, for example the Unix `indent` command.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Emacs provides commands to modify indentation, including hitting `Tab` on a given line.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Elastic tabstops is a tabulation style which requires support from the text editor, where entire blocks of text are kept automatically aligned when the length of one line in the block changes.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] In more complicated code, the programmer may lose track of block boundaries while reading the code.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] This is often experienced in large sections of code containing many compound statements nested to many levels of indentation.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] As the programmer scrolls to the bottom of a huge set of nested statements, they may lose track of context – such as the control structure at the top of the block.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Long compound statements can be a code smell of over complexity which can be solved by refactoring.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Programmers who rely on counting the opening braces may have difficulty with indentation styles such as K&R, where the starting brace is not visually separated from its control statement.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Programmers who rely more on indentations will gain more from styles that are vertically compact, such as K&R, because the blocks are shorter.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] To avoid losing track of control statements such as `for`, a large indentation can be used, such as an 8-unit-wide hard tab, along with breaking up large functions into smaller and more readable functions.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Linux is done this way, while using the K&R style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Some text editors allow the programmer to jump between the two corresponding braces of a block.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] For example, vi jumps to the brace enclosing the same block as the one under the cursor when pressing the `%` key.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Since the text cursor's `next` key (viz., the `n` key) retained directional positioning information (whether the `up` or `down` key was formerly pressed), the dot macro (the `.` key) could then be used to place the text cursor on the next brace, given a suitable coding style.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Instead, inspecting the block boundaries using the `%` key can be used to enforce a coding standard.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Another way to maintain block awareness is to use comments after the closing brace.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] A disadvantage is maintaining the same code in multiple locations – above and below the block.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Some editors provide support for maintaining block awareness.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] A folding editor can hide (fold) and reveal (unfold) blocks by indentation level.
[src:editorconfig/indentation-style] Some editors highlight matching braces when the cursor is positioned next to one.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] A **text editor** is interactive software that allows a user to edit plain text, such as Notepad.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] As source code is text, any text editor can be used to edit code, but a source-code editor is designed with features specifically intended for editing code.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some provide integration with software development tools and provide a debugging environment.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] There are important differences between plain text (created and edited by text editors) and rich text (such as that created by word processors or desktop publishing software).
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Plain text exclusively consists of character representation.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Each character is represented by a fixed-length sequence of one, two, or four bytes, or as a variable-length sequence of one to four bytes, in accordance to specific character encoding conventions, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 2022, Shift JIS, UTF-8, or UTF-16.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] These conventions define many printable characters, but also non-printing characters that control the flow of the text, such as space, line break, and page break.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Plain text contains no other information about the text itself, not even the character encoding convention employed.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Plain text is stored in text files, although text files do not exclusively store plain text.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Since the early days of computers, plain text was (once by necessity and now by convention) generally displayed using a monospaced font, such that horizontal alignment and columnar formatting were sometimes done using whitespace characters.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Rich text can be saved in binary format (e.g.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] DOC), text files adhering to a markup language (e.g.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] RTF or HTML), or in a hybrid form of both (e.g.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Text editors are intended to open and save text files containing either plain text or anything that can be interpreted as plain text, including the markup for rich text or the markup for something else (e.g.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Before text editors existed, computer text was punched into cards with keypunch machines.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Physical boxes of these thin cardboard cards were then inserted into a card reader.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Magnetic tape, drum and disk card image files created from such card decks often had no line-separation characters at all, and assumed fixed-length 80- or 90-character records.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] An alternative to cards was Punched tape.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] It could be created by some teleprinters (such as the Teletype), which used special characters to indicate ends of records.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some early operating systems included batch text editors, either integrated with language processors or as separate utility programs; one early example was the ability to edit SQUOZE source files for SCAT in the SHARE Operating System.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] The first interactive text editors were "line editors" oriented to teletypes: teleprinter-style or typewriter-style terminals that mechanically printed both input and output on the same continuous roll of paper, without an illuminated display.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Commands (often a single keystroke) effected edits to a file at an insertion point, that the operator needed to keep track of, called the "cursor".
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Edits were verified by typing a command to print a small section of the file, and periodically by printing the entire file.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] In some line editors, the cursor could be moved by commands that specified the line number in the file, text strings (context) for which to search, and eventually regular expressions.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Line editors were major improvements over keypunching.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some line editors could be used by keypunch; editing commands could be taken from a deck of cards and applied to a specified file.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some common line editors supported a "verify" mode in which change commands displayed the altered lines.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] An example configuration, circa 1975, was a Teletype Model 33 as a console to a PDP-11 using Version 6 Unix, manipulating text with the *ed*, the standard UNIX text editor.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] When computer terminals with video screens became available, screen-based text editors (sometimes called just "screen editors") became common.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] One of the earliest full-screen editors was O26, which was written for the operator console of the CDC 6000 series computers in 1967.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Another early full-screen editor was vi.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Written in the 1970s, it is still a standard editor on Unix and Linux operating systems.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Also written in the 1970s was the UCSD Pascal Screen Oriented Editor, which was optimized both for indented source code and general text.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Emacs, one of the first free and open-source software projects, is another early full-screen or real-time editor, one that was ported to many systems.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] The 1977 Commodore PET was the first mass-market computer to feature a full-screen editor.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] A full-screen editor's ease-of-use and speed (compared to the line-based editors) motivated many early purchases of video terminals.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] The core data structure in a text editor is the one that manages the string (sequence of characters) or list of records that represents the current state of the file being edited.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] While the former could be stored in a single long consecutive array of characters, the desire for text editors that could more quickly insert text, delete text, and undo/redo previous edits led to the development of more complicated sequence data structures.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] A typical text editor uses a gap buffer, a linked list of lines (as in PaperClip), a piece table, or a rope, as its sequence data structure.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some text editors are small and simple, while others offer broad and complex functions.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] For example, Unix and Unix-like operating systems have the pico editor (or a variant), but many also include the vi and Emacs editors.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Microsoft Windows systems come with the simple Notepad, though many people—especially programmers—prefer other editors with more features.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Under Apple Macintosh's classic Mac OS there was the native TeachText later replaced by SimpleText in 1994, which was replaced in Mac OS X by TextEdit, which combines features of a text editor with those typical of a word processor such as rulers, margins and multiple font selection.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] These features are not available simultaneously, but must be switched by user command, or through the program automatically determining the file type.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Most word processors can read and write files in plain text format, allowing them to open files saved from text editors.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Saving these files from a word processor, however, requires ensuring the file is written in plain text format, and that any text encoding or BOM settings will not obscure the file for its intended use.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Non-WYSIWYG word processors, such as WordStar, are more easily pressed into service as text editors, and in fact were commonly used as such during the 1980s.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] The default file format of these word processors often resembles a markup language, with the basic format being plain text and visual formatting achieved using non-printing control characters or escape sequences.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Later word processors like Microsoft Word store their files in a binary format and are almost never used to edit plain text files.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some text editors can edit unusually large files such as log files or an entire database placed in a single file.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Simpler text editors may just read files into the computer's main memory.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] With larger files, this may be a slow process, and the entire file may not fit.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some text editors do not let the user start editing until this read-in is complete.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Editing performance also often suffers in nonspecialized editors, with the editor taking seconds or even minutes to respond to keystrokes or navigation commands.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Specialized editors have optimizations such as only storing the visible portion of large files in memory, improving editing performance.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some editors are programmable, meaning, e.g., they can be customized for specific uses.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] With a programmable editor it is easy to automate repetitive tasks or, add new functionality or even implement a new application within the framework of the editor.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] One common motive for customizing is to make a text editor use the commands of another text editor with which the user is more familiar, or to duplicate missing functionality the user has come to depend on.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Software developers often use editor customizations tailored to the programming language or development environment they are working in.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Emacs can even be programmed to emulate Vi, its rival in the traditional editor wars of Unix culture.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] An important group of programmable editors uses REXX as a scripting language.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] These "orthodox editors" contain a "command line" into which commands and macros can be typed and text lines into which line commands and macros can be typed.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Most such editors are derivatives of ISPF/PDF EDIT or of XEDIT, IBM's flagship editor for VM/SP through z/VM.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Among them are THE, KEDIT, X2, Uni-edit, and SEDIT.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] A text editor written or customized for a specific use can determine what the user is editing and assist the user, often by completing programming terms and showing tooltips with relevant documentation.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Many text editors for software developers include source code syntax highlighting and automatic indentation to make programs easier to read and write.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Programming editors often let the user select the name of an include file, function or variable, then jump to its definition.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some also allow for easy navigation back to the original section of code by storing the initial cursor location or by displaying the requested definition in a popup window or temporary buffer.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Some editors implement this ability themselves, but often an auxiliary utility like ctags is used to locate the definitions.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Most text editors provide methods to duplicate and move text within the file, or between files.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Cut, copy and paste are often integrated with a system clipboard.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Text editors provide extensive facilities for searching and replacing strings of text, either individually, or groups of files in opened tabs or a selected folder.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] , and listing multiple results in one place.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Often—especially with older text editors—there is only one level of edit history remembered and successively issuing the undo command will only "toggle" the last change.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] Modern or more complex editors usually provide a multiple-level history such that issuing the undo command repeatedly will revert the document to successively older edits.
[src:editorconfig/text-editor] A separate redo command will cycle the edits "forward" toward the most recent changes.
