[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] A **whitespace character** is a character data element that represents white space when text is rendered for display by a computer.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] For example, a *space* character (U+0020 SPACE, ASCII 32) represents blank space such as a word divider in a Western script.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] A printable character results in output when rendered, but a whitespace character does not.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Instead, whitespace characters define the layout of text to a limited degree, interrupting the normal sequence of rendering characters next to each other.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The output of subsequent characters is typically shifted to the right (or to the left for right-to-left script) or to the start of the next line.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The effect of multiple sequential whitespace characters is cumulative such that the next printable character is rendered at a location based on the accumulated effect of preceding whitespace characters.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The origin of the term *whitespace* is rooted in the common practice of rendering text on white paper.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Normally, a whitespace character is *not* rendered as white.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] It affects rendering, but it is not itself rendered.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] A space character typically inserts horizontal space that is about as wide as a letter.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] For a monospaced font the width is the width of a letter, and for a variable-width font the width is font-specific.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Some fonts support multiple space characters that have different widths.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] A tab character typically inserts horizontal space that is based on tab stops which vary by application.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] A newline character sequence typically moves the render output location to the beginning of the next line.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] If one follows text, it does not actually result in whitespace.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] But, two sequential newline sequences between text blocks results in a blank line between the blocks.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The height of the blank line varies by application.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Using whitespace characters to lay out text is a convention.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Applications sometimes render whitespace characters as visible markup so that a user can see what is normally not visible.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Typically, a user types a space character by pressing spacebar, a tab character by pressing Tab ↹ and newline by pressing ↵ Enter.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The table below lists the twenty-five characters defined as whitespace ("WSpace=Y", "WS") characters in the Unicode Character Database.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Seventeen use a definition of whitespace consistent with the algorithm for bidirectional writing ("Bidirectional Character Type=WS") and are known as "Bidi-WS" characters.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The remaining characters may also be used, but are not of this "Bidi" type.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] : identical to U+0020, but not a point at which a line may be broken.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Normally a vertical line in vertical text or a horizontal line in horizontal text, but may also be a blank space in "stemless" fonts.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] U+2002 is canonically equivalent to this character; U+2002 is preferred.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] U+2003 is canonically equivalent to this character; U+2003 is preferred.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] U+2000 En Quad is canonically equivalent to this character; U+2002 is preferred.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] U+2001 Em Quad is canonically equivalent to this character; U+2003 is preferred.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In computer typography, sometimes equated to U+2009.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In fonts with monospaced digits, equal to the width of one digit.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] As wide as the narrow punctuation in a font, i.e. the advance width of the period or comma.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] ; one-fifth (sometimes one-sixth) of an em wide.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Unlike U+2002 to U+2008, its width may get adjusted in typesetting.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Similar in function to U+00A0 No-Break Space.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] A narrow space character, used in Mongolian to cause the final two characters of a word to take on different shapes.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] It is no longer classified as space character (i.e. in Zs category) in Unicode 6.3.0, even though it was in previous versions of the standard.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Used to indicate word boundaries to text processing systems when using scripts that do not use explicit spacing.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] , with the difference that the latter is used to indicate syllable boundaries, and should display a visible hyphen when the line breaks at it.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] When placed between two characters that would otherwise be connected, a ZWNJ causes them to be printed in their final and initial forms, respectively.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] When placed between two characters that would otherwise not be connected, a ZWJ causes them to be printed in their connected forms.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Can also be used to display joining forms in isolation.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] ) substitution with a single glyph, whilst still permitting use of individual joining forms (unlike ZWNJ).
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Similar to U+200B, but not a point at which a line may be broken.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Use as an indication of non-breaking is deprecated as of Unicode 3.2; see U+2060 instead.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Text editors, word processors, and desktop publishing software differ in how they represent whitespace on the screen, and how they represent spaces at the ends of lines longer than the screen or column width.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In some cases, spaces are shown simply as blank space; in other cases they may be represented by an interpunct or other symbols.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Many different characters (described below) could be used to produce spaces, and non-character functions (such as margins and tab settings) can also affect whitespace.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Many of the Unicode space characters were created for compatibility with classic print typography.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Even if digital typography has algorithmic kerning and justification, those space characters can be used to supplement the electronic formatting when needed.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In computer character encodings, there is a normal **general-purpose space** (Unicode character U+0020) whose width will vary according to the design of the typeface.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Typical values range from 1/5 em to 1/3 em (in digital typography an em is equal to the nominal size of the font, so for a 10-point font the space will probably be between 2 and 3.3 points).
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Sophisticated fonts may have differently sized spaces for bold, italic, and small-caps faces, and often compositors will manually adjust the width of the space depending on the size and prominence of the text.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In addition to this general-purpose space, it is possible to encode a space of a specific width.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] See the table above for a complete list.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Em dashes used as parenthetical dividers, and en dashes when used as word joiners, are usually set continuous with the text.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] However, such a dash can optionally be surrounded with a **hair space**, U+200A, or **thin space**, U+2009.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The hair space can be written in HTML by using the numeric character references `&#x200A;` or `&#8202;`, or the named entity `&hairsp;`.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The thin space is named entity `&thinsp;` and numeric references `&#x2009;` or `&#8201;`.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] These spaces are much thinner than a normal space (except in a monospaced (non-proportional) font), with the hair space in particular being the thinnest of horizontal whitespace characters.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In most programming language syntax, whitespace characters can be used to separate tokens.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] For a free-form language, whitespace characters are ignored by code processors (i.e. compiler).
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Even when language syntax requires white space, often multiple whitespace characters are treated the same as a single.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In an off-side rule language, indentation white space is syntactically significant.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In the satirical and contrarian language called Whitespace, whitespace characters are the only significant characters and normal text is ignored.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Good use of white space in source code can group related logic and make the code easier to understand.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Excessive use of whitespace, including at the end of a line where it provides no rendering behavior, is considered a nuisance.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Most languages only recognize whitespace characters that have an ASCII code.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] They disallow most or all of the Unicode codes listed above.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The C language defines whitespace characters to be "space, horizontal tab, new-line, vertical tab, and form-feed".
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] The HTTP network protocol requires different types of whitespace to be used in different parts of the protocol; it requires single space characters between items in the status line, a CR/LF pair at the end of a line, and "linear whitespace" in header values.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Typical command-line parsers use the space character to delimit arguments.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] A value with an embedded space character is problematic since it causes the value to parse as multiple arguments.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Typically, a parser allows for escaping the normal argument parsing by enclosing the text in quotes.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] the command would, instead, attempt to list files or directories named `foo` and `bar`.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Some markup languages, such as SGML, preserve whitespace as written.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Web markup languages such as XML and HTML treat whitespace characters specially, including space characters, for programmers' convenience.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] One or more space characters read by conforming display-time processors of those markup languages are collapsed to 0 or 1 space, depending on their semantic context.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] For example, double (or more) spaces within text are collapsed to a single space, and spaces which appear on either side of the "`=`" that separates an attribute name from its value have no effect on the interpretation of the document.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Element end tags can contain trailing spaces, and empty-element tags in XML can contain spaces before the "`/>`".
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In these languages, unnecessary whitespace increases the file size, and so may slow network transfers.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] On the other hand, unnecessary whitespace can also incon­spicu­ously mark code for identification purposes, in a manner similar to but less overtly obvious than the way comments in code can.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] This can be of benefit in proving an infringement of license or copyright claim if the code was blatantly copied and pasted.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In XML attribute values, sequences of whitespace characters are treated as a single space when the document is read by a parser.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Whitespace in XML element content is not changed in this way by the parser, but an application receiving information from the parser may choose to apply similar rules to element content.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] An XML document author can use the `xml:space="preserve"` attribute on an element to instruct the parser to discourage the downstream application from altering whitespace in that element's content.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In most HTML elements, a sequence of whitespace characters is treated as a single *inter-word separator*, which may manifest as a single space character when rendering text in a language that normally inserts such space between words.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Conforming HTML renderers apply literal whitespace behaviour to certain elements: those inside `<pre>...</pre>` tags, and those where CSS property `white-space` is set to pre or pre-wrap.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In these elements, space characters will not be "collapsed" into inter-word separators.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In MediaWiki markup, as well as the `<pre>...</pre>` there is an optional `<poem>...</poem>` tag, which also preserves whitespace.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] In both XML and HTML, the non-breaking space character, along with other "non-standard" spaces, is not treated as collapsible whitespace.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Such usage is similar to multiword file names written for operating systems and applications that are confused by embedded space codes—such file names instead use an underscore (_) as a word separator, as_in_this_phrase.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Another such symbol is U+2422 ␢ BLANK SYMBOL, which was used on coding forms in the early years of computer programming.
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] Keypunch operators interpreted it as an "explicit space".
[src:editorconfig/whitespace-character] It was used in BCDIC, EBCDIC, and ASCII-1963.
